E. styeloides (
Traustedt, 1882
)
has zooids about 1cm long, erect on stolons attached to the substrate on their whole length. The siphons are long and distant from each other. The tunic is glassy but often covered with debris. The body musculature is essentially transverse on the whole width of the body sides. There are 15 rows of stigmata. The stomach is elongated with a well marked groove. The rectum is not very long and opens a little anteriorly to the top of the gut loop. The main difference of this species comes from the large testis of numerous lobes in a half circle overlapping a large part of the intestine (
Monniot C. 1983 a
Fig. 3
A,B). The sperm duct ends at the anus level or anteriorly to it. E. s tyeloides was considered as a Caribbean species by Goodbody & Jones ( 2006 and synonymy) but was also recorded from the Mediterranean sea (
Monniot C. & Monniot F. 1987
), from Mozambique (
Monniot C. 1997
), from Palau (
Monniot F. & Monniot C. 1996
) and from Venezuala (
Rocha et al. 2010
).
